  "method": "We propose FACT-MIX pretraining: a dual objective that couples invariance to imperceptible, human-preserving perturbations with explicit sensitivity to semantic, counterfactual edits—so the model learns what to ignore and what to react to. Build two perturbation banks per domain. (a) Factual, perceptual-preserving variants: for vision/audio use small spatial/time shifts, mild blurs, compression, and spectral jitter within perceptual thresholds; for text use paraphrases, synonym/inflection substitutions, punctuation/casing noise, and token/span drops. (b) Counterfactual variants that minimally alter surface form but flip meaning: for text, controlled role swaps or keyword replacements that change predicate–argument structure; for vision/audio, attribute flips or localized edits that change class-defining factors. During pretraining, draw triplets (x, x+, x−) where x+ is factual and x− is counterfactual.\n\nTrain a single model with a dual consistency–contrastive loss. First, impose factual consistency: align predictions pθ(y|x) and pθ(y|x+) via symmetric KL and align intermediate representations z(x), z(x+) via cosine or InfoNCE positives. Second, impose counterfactual separation: push apart z(x) and z(x−) with a margin, and apply unlikelihood on labels inconsistent with the counterfactual (penalize high probability of y on x− and of y− on x, x+). To prevent brittleness to token- or patch-level perturbations, add salience-aware masking: randomly drop or synonymize spans/patches while encouraging output stability, and occasionally replace salient spans with semantically opposite content to enforce sensitivity. A lightweight conditioning-dependency regularizer compares the model’s token-level or patch-level probabilities with and without the conditioning signal and penalizes low dependency on the input when predicting content words, discouraging reliance on spurious priors.\n\nStabilize features against high-frequency, spatially inconsistent noise with gradient-smoothing augmentation. Apply random shifts/jitters and compute a Normalized Discontinuity-style penalty: encourage small changes in feature maps and losses across these micro-transforms. This smoothness term reduces the model’s incentive to encode brittle edges and checkerboard artifacts that adversaries exploit, without introducing test-time defenses. For sequence models, also use selective token mixing: during training, partially replace corrupted or low-confidence tokens with their clean counterparts at a small mixing ratio to prevent cascading error amplification while maintaining exposure to noise.\n\nFinally, equip the encoder with a multi-view aggregation head that learns k latent \"view\" vectors per example. Feed each perturbed factual view x+ through the shared backbone and aggregate via permutation-invariant pooling (e.g., max or log-sum-exp) over the k latent views to produce a single representation used by the task head. Train with the dual loss on pooled outputs and per-view features; at inference, run a single forward pass with the learned latent views (no input augmentations), so robustness benefits persist without test-time cost.",
  "rationale": "Adversarial brittleness stems from models exploiting spurious, high-frequency, and position-specific cues and from miscalibration about which input factors truly drive targets. Pretraining with a dual objective addresses both sides: factual consistency teaches invariance to imperceptible, human-preserving perturbations, while counterfactual separation and unlikelihood teach sensitivity when meaning truly changes. This calibrates the decision boundary around human semantics rather than surface quirks.\n\nThe gradient-smoothing penalty induced by micro-shifts reduces feature discontinuities that correlate with vulnerability to small Lp perturbations, while selective token mixing prevents instability from compounding errors. The conditioning-dependency regularizer keeps the model anchored to its inputs rather than language or class priors, and the learned multi-view aggregation internalizes robustness to diverse factual perturbations so no ensembles or test-time defenses are needed. All costs are borne at training time; inference uses a single forward pass.",
