  "method": "Universal-Perturbation-Invariant Pretraining (UPI-Pretrain). We pretrain the backbone to make its task-relevant representation invariant to a bank of human-imperceptible perturbations, so that standard fine-tuning and inference require no test-time defenses. For each sample, we form a tuple of one clean view and several perturbed views drawn from (i) conventional stochastic augmentations, and (ii) a small, learnable universal-perturbation bank implemented as input prompts added in pixel/frequency space under an Lp and perceptual constraint. The bank contains a handful of global and class-conditional prompts; it is optimized to maximize model loss/uncertainty on a moving target backbone while remaining imperceptible, and updated with an uncertainty-guided EMA so that harder samples drive stronger prompt updates without instability.\n\nWe treat perturbations as a domain shift and factor the backbone’s pre-logit representation into z_shared (robust, task-relevant) and z_delta (nuisance, perturbation-specific). A contrastive consistency loss pulls together all views of the same sample in z_shared and pushes apart different samples. Simultaneously, a lightweight domain discriminator with a gradient-reversal layer removes perturbation information from z_shared, while an auxiliary head on z_delta predicts the perturbation type, encouraging nuisance absorption into z_delta. Classification (or label-conditioned contrastive) losses are applied only on z_shared so the decision boundary depends on perturbation-invariant features.\n\nTo further enlarge decision radii, we insert a prototype-based discriminant layer before logits. Class prototypes are learned in the shared latent space with cosine similarity and an additive angular margin; we enforce that every perturbed view remains closest to its clean-class prototype and far from others, and we add a single-pass uncertainty head trained on this embedding. During pretraining the uncertainty is only used to (i) weight hard-example losses and (ii) steer the prompt-bank EMA; at test time, the backbone runs as-is with no extra defenses.\n\nWe augment the above with a mix-and-separate pretext: randomly mix pairs of samples and their perturbations in input space (and/or feature space) and train a small separation head sharing the backbone to recover the two samples’ clean-class logits, while the main head receives standard mixup targets. This compels the representation to linearly disentangle content from nuisance perturbations and reduces reliance on brittle, high-frequency cues.\n\nTraining recipe: warm-start the backbone for a short phase with standard supervised or label-conditioned contrastive learning on clean+weakly-augmented views, then activate the perturbation bank, domain-adversarial alignment, prototype-margin loss, and mix-and-separate head. Use 3–6 prompts in the bank (1–2 global, 2–4 class-conditional), constrain their L∞ norm (e.g., ε≈2/255–4/255) and optionally low-pass filter to preserve imperceptibility. Optimize the total loss as a weighted sum of contrastive consistency, classification/proto-margin, domain-adversarial, perturbation-type prediction (on z_delta), and mix-and-separate objectives. Fine-tune on the downstream task normally; inference uses the plain backbone without test-time defenses or extra passes.",
  "rationale": "Training for perturbation invariance at pretraining time removes the need for expensive test-time defenses: the model has already learned to base decisions on features that are stable across a family of imperceptible attacks. A learnable universal-perturbation bank provides strong, hard augmentations without multi-step inner-loop attacks, and uncertainty-guided updates focus it where the model is fragile. Treating perturbations as a domain and explicitly factoring representations into shared vs nuisance channels, combined with gradient-reversal alignment, is an efficient way to purge attack-specific information from the decision-making subspace.\n\nPrototype-margin constraints increase inter-class separation and enforce that all perturbed views of a sample map near the same class prototype, which widens the margin against worst-case small perturbations. Finally, a mix-and-separate auxiliary task encourages linear disentanglement of content and nuisance, reducing reliance on non-robust, high-frequency cues. Together these pretraining objectives and augmentations yield robustness with zero added cost at inference time.",
